<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-460-100  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 460 100.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  June 1990 v8 n6 p78(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Font flurries promise confusion, new options: competition meanslower prices.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bender, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Font-rendering software is clearly the direction in whichmicrocomputer fonts are headed, but the question of whose fontsoftware will be standard, if any, becomes cloudier as IBMendorses Adobe PostScript for OS/2 and other platforms whileMicrosoft forges an alliance with Apple to develop the TrueTypefont technology and TrueImage page description language, whichwill support both TrueType and PostScript Type 1 fonts.andO;Hewlett-Packard has incorporated Agfa Compugraphic's Intellifonttechnology into its LaserJet III, and HP's overwhelming dominancein the laser printer market means IBM and Microsoft will have tosupport Intellifont as well.andP;  The long-term winner in all of thisis the end user, as the intense competition drives down the priceof font software.andP;  Until the arrival of TrueImage printers,PostScript remains the best alternative for document portability.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FontsSoftware DesignPrintersCompetitionMarket Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Who's who in scalable fonts. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>